occurrences.line_text: Till on a day (that day is euery Prime,
That seemd as fresh as Flora in her prime,
They all as glad, as birdes of ioyous Prime,
Early and late it rong, at euening and at prime.
Then gan this Realme renewe her passed prime:
Gather therefore the Rose, whilest yet is prime,
And her conception of the ioyous Prime,
And with fresh colours decke the wanton Prime,
When as mans age was in his freshest prime,
In prime of youthly yeares, when first the flowre
The time was once, in my first prime of yeares,
Whom that most noble Briton Prince so long
Great Gorgon, Prince of darknesse and dead night,
Was neuer Prince so faithfull and so faire,
Was neuer Prince so meeke and debonaire;
The house of mightie Prince it seemd to bee:
Prince Arthur meets with Vna great-
For this young Prince, when first to armes he fell;
For whose deliuera[n]ce she this Prince doth thither guide.
Whom when the Prince, to battell new addrest,
When as the noble Prince had marked well,
As this good Prince redeemd the Redcrosse knight from bands.
Faire virgin (said the Prince) ye me require
Aread Prince Arthur, crowne of Martiall band?
And sad remembraunce now the Prince amoues,
Prince Arthur gaue a boxe of Diamond sure,
Withhold, O soueraine Prince, your hasty hond
Sith her Prince Arthur of proud ornaments
Prince Arthur is, that wonnes in Faerie lond;
That neuer earthly Prince in such aray
Prince Arthur, flowre of grace and nobilesse,
Indeed (then said the Prince) the euill donne
Nath'lesse the Prince would not forsake his sell:
Now was the Prince in daungerous distresse,
The Prince now stood, hauing his weapon broke;
So rag'd Prince Arthur twixt his foemen twaine,
And on the hauberk stroke the Prince so sore,
The Prince, with patience and sufferaunce sly
But him in strength and skill the Prince surpast,
Wroth was the Prince, and sory yet withall,
And to the Prince bowing with reuerence dew,
The Briton Prince recou'ring his stolne sword,
Till him the Prince with gentle court did bord;
Or grace of earthly Prince so soueraine,
Certes (then said the Prince) I God auow,
The Prince by chaunce did on a Lady light,
To whom the Prince in curteous manner said;
The Prince was inly moued at her speach,
From this renowmed Prince deriued arre,
The Prince him selfe halfe seemeth to offend,
Prince Arthur them repelles, and fowle
To see a cruell fight doen by the Prince this day.
Till that the Prince seeing her wofull plight,
Soone as the Carle from farre the Prince espyde,
Which to preuent, the Prince his mortall speare
Proofe be thou Prince, the prowest man aliue,
The whiles the Prince prickt with reprochfull shame,
So mightily the Briton Prince him rouzd
Then thought the Prince all perill sure was past,
The famous Briton Prince and Faerie knight,
And seeke aduentures, as he with Prince Arthur went.
The Prince of grace, to let him runne that turne.
And eke the Prince like treaty handeled,
In which accord the Prince was also plaste,
The Prince and Guyon equally byliue
It was a famous Present for a Prince,
Nor Prince, nor pere it is, whose loue hath gryde
Of courteous knights, the Prince, and Faery gent,
But fairest fortune to the Prince befell,
Which when the Prince beheld, a lothfull sight,
Thus did the Prince that wearie night outweare,
Prince Arthur heares of Florimell:
It lets not scarse this Prince to breath at all,
To whom the Prince; Dwarfe, comfort to thee take,
And from Prince Arthur fled with wings of idle feare.
Which with the Prince of Darknesse fell somewhile,
The Queene of loue, & Prince of peace fro[m] heauen blest.
His owne deare Lord Prince Arthure came that way,
And euer when the Prince vnto him spake,
The Prince did wonder much, yet could not ghesse
The noble Prince, who neuer heard one word
Whom when the Prince beheld, he gan to rew
How all the way the Prince on footpace traced,
The Prince on foot, not wonted so to fare;
Where when he saw the Prince in armour bright,
Eftsoones the Prince tooke downe those Ladies twaine
Had not the noble Prince his readie stroke represt.
Whereat the Prince full wrath, his strong right hand
Then gan the Prince at leasure to inquire
She deare besought the Prince of remedie:
Prince Arthur stints their strife.
Now after that Prince Arthur graunted had,
Whom straight the Prince ensuing, in together far'd.
The Prince halfe rapt, began on her to dote:
And eke the Prince, when as he them auized,
Vpon all which the Briton Prince made seasure,
But her the Prince through his well wonted grace,
Thus when the Prince had perfectly compylde
Whom when the Briton Prince a farre beheld
The Prince yet being fresh vntoucht afore;
To whom the Prince thus goodly well replied;
Prince Arthure and Sir Artegall,
To whom the Prince; Certes me needeth more
Then Artegall gan of the Prince enquire,
Certes I wote not well (the Prince then sayd)
Soone after whom the Prince arriued there,
The Briton Prince him readie did awayte,
But the braue Prince for honour and for right,
Either the Prince in peeces to haue torne
Oft drew the Prince vnto his charret nigh,
Yet could the Prince not nigh vnto him goe,
Yet still the Prince pursew'd him close behind,
And there the Prince, as victour of that day,
And turne we to the noble Prince, where late
The whiles the Prince there kept the entrance still:
The prayses of that Prince so manifold:
The Briton Prince was sore empassionate,
All which when as the Prince had heard and seene,
Prince Arthur takes the enterprize
The noble Prince, and righteous Artegall,
The noble Briton Prince, with his braue Peare;
It was not long, till that the Prince arriued
There did the Prince him leaue in deadly swound,
So all attonce they on the Prince did thonder;
And after them the Prince as swiftly sped,
The whiles the Prince hard preased in betweene,
Long sought the Prince, but when he found no more
Prince Arthure ouercomes the great
The Prince staid not his aunswere to deuize,
That the bold Prince was forced foote to giue
Which vncouth vse when as the Prince perceiued,
Which when the Prince heard tell, his heart gan earne
The armed Prince, with shield so blazing bright,
Appointed by that mightie Faerie Prince,
till she Prince Arthure fynd,
Prince Arthur and young Timias, which met
Then gan the Prince, of her for to demand,
And all the way the Prince sought to appease
Wherewith the Prince sore moued, there auoud,
Therefore the Prince, whom great affaires in mynd
What fortune to the Briton Prince did lite,
The Prince according to the former token,
To whom the Prince, him fayning to embase,
But the bold Prince defended him so well,
Whereof whenas the Prince was well aware,
So likewise turnde the Prince vpon the Knight,
But when the Prince had once him plainely eyde,
Ne would the Prince him euer foot forsake,
There did the Prince him ouertake anone,
That euen the Prince his basenesse did despize,
Whom when the Prince so deadly saw dismayd,
Whom when the Prince so felly saw to rage,
And were not, that the Prince did him appeaze,
The Prince himselfe there all that night did rest,
The wrathfull Prince, & wrought her husbands peace,
For all that night, the whyles the Prince did rest
The morrow next the Prince did early rize,
He of the Prince his life receiued late,
The gentle Prince not farre away they spyde,
But the stout Prince, with much more steddy stowre
Not so the Prince: for his well learned speare
The Prince soone hearkned, and his life forgaue.
The Prince much mused at such villenie,
Whereas the Prince himselfe lay all alone,
Whereat the Prince awaking, when he spyde
Prince Arthure ouercomes Disdaine,
They met Prince Arthure with Sir Enias,
And to the Prince thus sayd; See you Sir Knight,
The Prince assented, and then he streight way
Which when the Prince beheld, there standing by,
But yet the Prince so well enured was
Eftsoones the Prince to him full nimbly stept,
Certes (sayd then the Prince) the God is iust,
Procur'd the Prince his cruell hand to stay,
And let him rise. Then thus the Prince gan say;
Vnto the Prince of Picteland bordering nere,
Deposed was from Princedome soueraine,
Quoth she, his princely puissance doth abate,
So proud she shyned in her Princely state,
All hurtlen forth, and she with Princely pace,
They backe returned to the Princely Place;
With royall pomp and Princely maiestie;
In princely pompe, of all the world obayd;
With princely gifts of yuorie and gold,
Those same with stately grace, and princely port
But full of Princely bounty and great mind,
And her proud portance, and her princely gest,
Banisht from Princely bowre to wastfull wood:
So goodly graue, and full of princely aw,
There Iustice first her princely rule begonne.
That she a Queene, and come of Princely kynd,
And als' of princely grace to be inclyn'd thereto.
But after all her princely entertayne,
But she, whose Princely breast was touched nere
The goodly praise of Princely curtesie,
In liuing Princes court none euer knew
Fell from high Princes courts, or Ladies bowres,
That greatest Princes presence might behold.
Of all, that royall Princes court became,
The large discourse of royall Princes state.
Thus when that Princes wrath was pacifide,
Whom Princes late displeasure left in bands,
In Princes court,---The rest she would haue said,
Which mortall Princes wore, whiles they on earth did rayne.
There chaunced to the Princes hand to rize,
By which all earthly Princes she doth farre surmount.
Gathered the Princes of the people loose,
Euen seuen hundred Princes, which maintaynd
Mote Princes place beseeme so deckt to bee.
Ne tastest Princes pleasures, ne doest spred
But Timias, the Princes gentle Squire,
That greatest Princes liuing it mote well delight.
Of Alexander, and his Princes fiue,
Whom greatest Princes court would welcome fayne;
In Princes Court doe hap to sprout againe,
Sprung of the auncient stocke of Princes straine,
His Leman from the Stygian Princes boure.
That powre he also doth to Princes lend,
And of weake Princes to be Patronesse,
That many Princes she in wealth exceedes,
The skill whereof to Princes hearts he doth reueale.
Are wont in Princes courts to worke great scath and hindrance.
Vpon the thrones of mortall Princes tend,
Gainst loiall Princes, all this cursed plot,
That herein doest all earthly Princes pas?
Into the Princes shield, where it empight;
Not so the Princes, but with restlesse force,
And well beseemeth that in Princes hall
The spoiles of Princes hang'd, which were in battel won.
To be a Princes Paragone esteemed,
And in the Princes gardin daily wrought:
During which space she there as Princess rained,
Of Princesse worthy, scarse them bad arise.
And that great Princesse too exceeding prowd,
Which all through that great Princesse pride did fall
And thou, O fairest Princesse vnder sky,
And to that mighty Princesse did complaine
Haue made thee souldier of that Princesse bright,
A Princesse of great powre, and greater pride,
A Princesse of great powre and maiestie,
Serues her, as any Princesse vnder sky,
As their true Liege and Princesse naturall;
Riches, renowme, and principality,
But both him honor'd as their principall,
Oft spilles the principall, to saue the part;
Doubting sad end of principle vnsound:
Calidore brings Priscilla home,
But faire Priscilla (so that Lady hight)
Where when he saw his faire Priscilla by,
Ne ought would buy, how euer prisd with measure,
His Lady left as a prise martiall,
Had left that Turneyment for beauties prise,
He ment to make them know their follies prise,
What time the fame of this renowmed prise
Through which, when Paris brought his famous prise
So vnto him they did addeeme the prise
By meanes his leg through his late luckelesse prise,
And prises to them placed at their pleasure,
To make the prises of the rest more deare.
A diuerse dreame out of his prison darke,
Vnto her natiue prison to retourne:
And ouercommen kept in prison long,
Stout Ferrex and sterne Porrex him in prison threw.
In wretched prison long he did remaine,
And grudge, in so streight prison to be prest,
And meant vnto her prison to haue brought,
So soone as he the Prison dore did pas,
Her body, late the prison of sad paine,
As if he had in prison long bene pent:
Vnto the prison in her ioyous glee,
To whom the keyes of euery prison dore
Did secretly out of her prison steale;
Thence she commaunded me to prison new;
Who now long time had lyen in prison sad,
To open vnto him the prison dore,
And in this prison put him here with me:
One prison fittest is to hold vs two:
Vnto the prison, where her hart did thrall remaine.
Which had her Lord in her base prison pent,
She for that yron prison did enquire,
The which she bore, the whiles in prison she did dwell.
He found the meanes that Prisoner vp to reare;
He bound that pitteous Lady prisoner, now relest,
In hope to take him prisoner, where he stood on ground.
The which the prisoner points vnto the free,
And now perforce they haue him prisoner taken;
And from the other fiftie soone the prisoner fet.
Then was there brought, as prisoner to the barre,
That Damzell, whom he held as wrongfull prisonere.
Whom she had causd be kept as prisonere,
Poore prisoners to relieue with gratious ayd,
One day as he did all his prisoners vew,
Till some, which did the sundry prisoners knowe,
But ioy that for his sake I suffer prisonment.
And shut vp fast within her prisons blind,
The priuate state, and make the life vnsweet:
A priuate life led in Albania,
And many a priuate oft doth ouerthrow.
And eke of priuate persons many moe,
Ne priuate iarre, ne spite of enemis
And also of their priuate loues beguyled;
To feeding of her priuate fire, which boyld
And from the country back to priuate farmes he scorsed.
And griefull pittie priuately bemone.
He by a priuie Posterne tooke his flight,
How to escape. At last in priuie wise
And priuie spials plast in all his way,
The priuie guilt whereof makes him alway
Ne priuie be vnto your treasures graue.
But she as Fayes are wont, in priuie place
He askt, what priuie tokens he did beare.
Who priuie was, and partie in the case:
In sort as he him schooled priuily:
To kindle heat of corage priuily:
Which to extirpe, he laid him priuily
It was auoided quite, and throwne out priuily.
Which he perceiuing, euer priuily
That the rich metall lurked priuily,
Priuily moystening his horrid cheek.
Did priuily put coles vnto his secret fire.
And Ate eke prouokt him priuily,
Me when as he had priuily espide,
Priuily pricked with thy lustfull powres,
Vppon the ground, which kindled priuily,
He found that they had festred priuily,
Had vnderneath, him armed priuily.
Thereat the Elfe did blush in priuitee,
Him oft and oft I askt in priuitie,
Of all my loue and all my priuitie;
For all his dayes he drownes in priuitie,
And that for reasons speciall priuitie:
Yet neither shewed to other their hearts priuity.
Once to approch to her in priuity,
She shut vp all her plaint in priuy griefe;
Empoisned was with priuy lust, and gealous dred.
Where he through priuy griefe, and horrour vaine,
For priuy loue his brest empierced had,
And in a priuy place, betwixt vs hight,
A priuy token, which betweene them past,
And shut vp all his plaint in priuy paine.
Labour'd in vaine, to haue recur'd their prize,
Britomart winnes the prize from all,
The prize of her, which did in beautie most excell.
To challenge her anew, as his owne prize,
To be the prize of beautie and of might;
Assembled were, that glorious prize to gaine.
Then all with one consent did yeeld the prize
The prize, to knights of Maydenhead that day,
Where beauties prize shold win that pretious spoyle:
The prize of beautie still hath ioyned beene;
The third dayes prize vnto that straunger Knight,
And eke the famous prize of beauty from them wonne.
And forst the burden of their prize to stay.
The honour of the prize should be adiudg'd by those.
As if the prize she gotten had almost,
Should as his purchast prize with him conuay
Was his owne purchase and his onely prize,
From his moist eies, and like two streames procead;
They stayd a while: and forth she gan proceed:
Nigh to his vtmost date he saw proceed,
Yet stayd they not, but forward did proceed,
But to the rest, which in this Quest proceed
Which from that goodly glorious flowre proceed,
Did first proceed, then which none more vpright,
He purposd to proceed, what so be fall,
And to his voyage gan againe proceed:
To heale your selues, and must proceed alone
She stayd, and foorth Duessa gan proceede,
But ere they could proceede vnto the place,
So from immortall race he does proceede,
And draw from on this iourney to proceede.
Then he forth on his iourney did proceede,
More sharpe then points of needles did proceede,
But when as yet she saw him to proceede,
Least any more such practise should proceede.
Vnknowen was) whence all this did proceede,
She on her way cast forward to proceede,
Proceeded, yet each one felt secretly
Proceeded, lo now is reueald to thee.
Late left beyond that Ydle lake, proceedes
Who now to perils great for iustice sake proceedes.
Who forth proceeding with sad sober cheare,
Proceeding to the midst, he still did stand,
For enmitie, that of no ill proceeds,
The further processe of her hidden griefe;
And solemne feast proclaimd throughout the land,
Hath lately caus'd to be proclaim'd each where
Their Lord and Patrone loud did him proclame,
In sort as through the world I did proclame,
Does ouerthrow, and troublous warre proclame:
But at the last the trompets did proclame
On which that cursed Idole farre proclamed,
Proclaymed ioy and peace through all his state;
And him entreat for grace, that had procur'd her paine.
Procur'd the Prince his cruell hand to stay,
Ne let vaine feares procure your needlesse smart,
Then she began a treatie to procure,
That secretly doth vs procure to fall,
As beauties louely baite, that doth procure
Yet had no meanes to comfort, nor procure her glee.
And liking in her yet vntamed heart procure.
Of the faire Alma greatly were procured,
That it was no old sore, which his new paine procured.
He now t'abhorre and loath her person had procured.
That it prodigious seemes in common peoples sight.
All that behold so strange prodigious sight,
Whence being forth produc'd, when she perceiued
And after her did Paridell produce
And new accusements to produce in place:
Young knight, what euer that dost armes professe,
Gainst all, that truth or vertue doe professe,
Yet greater loue to me then her he did professe.
Where though reuengefull vow she did professe,
That court'sie doth as well as armes professe,
Yet did her face and former parts professe
Hence to professe: for shame is to adorne
Friendship professed with vnfained hart,
Gainst all those knights, as their professed fone,
At Scudamour, both his professed fone.
For she her selfe professeth mortall foe
And Regan greater loue to him profest,
That loue is not, where most it is profest,
That to all Ladies, which haue it profest,
Scorne the faire offer of good will profest;
Then to be false in loue, profest a virgine wife.
Profest to her true friendship and affection sweet.
And friends profest are chaungd to foemen fell:
Each one profest to be her paramoure,
In friends profest, and so great outrage donne:
For from the first that I her loue profest,
Ne more sincere in word and deed profest;
That blame it is to him, that armes profest,
But I am bound by vow, which I profest
That he, which was their Capitaine profest,
To shew the courtesie by him profest,
Proffer thy giftes, and fitter seruaunts entertaine.
And proffer made by force her to reprize:
Some proffer made with him for her to fight.
And thus bespake; Sir knight, your bounteous proffe[r]
The which thy proffred curtesie denayd?
But each his paines to others profit still employd.
Of marchants farre, for profits therein praysd,
Here ended Brutus sacred progenie,
For from thy wombe a famous Progenie
Here to account the endlesse progenie
He left three sonnes, his famous progeny,
And happie father of faire progeny:
And shewes the famous Progeny
To count the seas abundant progeny,
The father of that fatall progeny,
The substances of natures fruitfull progenyes.
So forth they both yfere make their progresse,
Before his feet her selfe she did proiect,
He would at her request prolong her nephews daies.
Ne may a man prolong, nor shorten it;
That mak'st thy selfe his dayes-man, to prolong
Sought by all meanes his dolour to prolong,
Did yield himselfe right willing to prolong his date.
Long life, thereby did more prolong their paine.
Till then your challenges ye may prolong;
That loues not me, then doe it not prolong,
But Iustice, though her dome she doe prolong,
And though good lucke prolonged hath thy date,
That so their liues might be prolonged late.
It told, how first Prometheus did create
Doth promise hope of helpe, and timely grace,
Did with sure promise of her good indeuour,
Through promise to afford her timely aide,
The which for promise of great meed, vs draue
Therefore now yeeld, as ye did promise make,
He promised to bring me at that howre,
That promist ayde the tempest to withstand:
Thy Gransire Nereus promist to adorne?
She promist kisses sweet, and sweeter things
And for his loue him promist libertie at last.
And after promist large amends to make.
But promist him, what euer wight she weare,
And more then that, she promist that she would,
Promist, if she would free him from that case,
In which ye promist, as ye were a Knight,
And promist to performe his precept well,
Of them, that to him buxome are and prone:
When he his sentence thus pronounced had,
Large Lisianassa, and Pronï¿½a sage,
From whence she might behold that battailles proof
And ioyd to make proofe of her crueltie
Yet of his prowesse proofe he since hath made
But now by proofe all otherwise I weene;
To proofe of passing wonders hath full often vsd.
For proofe thereof, this euening, as thou art,
Proofe be thou Prince, the prowest man aliue,
But all for praise, and proofe of manly might,
Ne brauer proofe in any, of thy powre
Where also proofe of thy prow valiaunce
Thy dayes abridge, through proofe of puissance,
I will with proofe of last extremity,
After the proofe of prowesse ended well,
For dread of her displeasures vtmost proofe.
Did shun the proofe thereof and it auoyded light.
Streight forth issewd a Knight all arm'd to proofe,
